A black box in the car?
U.S. road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the decaying highway system and believe they have found the solution in a small black box that fits in the dashboard of every car.
The devices that record every mile driven and report the information to authorities are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and state planning offices to revise the outdated system for financing U.S. roads.
The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have teamed up with environmental groups and advocate that the government can use the small boxes to record the kilometres it has traveled – and possibly where they have been traveled – and then use the information to calculate tax bills.
The tea party is horrified.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of privacy concerns.
However, while there is no agreement in Congress on a course of action, several states are no longer waiting.
They are currently considering how to switch over the next ten years to a system where drivers pay per mile driven.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is really a must for our country.
“It’s nothing we’re only potentially going to use,” said Hasan Ikhrata, managing director of Southern California Assn. of Governments, which plans to record miles driven by all California drivers in the state starting in 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
The technology for that is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is funded from the taxes Americans pay at the gas station, is bankrupt.
But in America, there is not as much fueling as it used to be.
Cars use less gasoline.
The state oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 eurocents per liter) has not risen in 20 years.
Politicians do not dare to raise the tax even by a cent at high fuel prices.
“The gasoline tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, an expert on traffic legislation at the University of Minnesota.
Its state recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile-based payment system.
“This is the most meaningful alternative in the long run,” he said.
Bureaucrats call it a mile-based user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea is appealing to urban liberals, because the tax could be used, for example, to influence driving behaviour in a way that reduces congestion and climate-damaging exhaust gases.
The California planners rely on the system to develop strategies to achieve the state’s ambitious, legally enshrined climate change goals.
But Republican Bill Shuster of Pennsylvania, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also fascinated by the idea of having drivers pay for the distance they have traveled.
“This is not a tax that disappears in a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers, who in a 2011 report called on Congress to move toward mileage-based billing.
The U.S. Senate last year approved a $90 million expensive pilot project that would include 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the move, responding to the concerns of deputies from rural areas, who often have to travel many miles on their way to work or to the city in everyday life.
Nevertheless, several states and major cities are moving in this direction on their own.
The most engaged is Oregon, which is currently hiring 5,000 drivers for the nation’s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the mileage fees instead of the petroleum tax to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering this.
Illinois tests it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport ministries of 17 states on the east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is currently investigating how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the devices, drivers were skeptical about thinking that the government could track any of their movements.
“Concerning Big Brother and things like that were a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and earnings management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn't want it.
As the test started, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website, “It would be relatively easy to turn the tachographs into adult monitoring devices.”
There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is among a number of states now looking for affordable technology that allows the state to track the miles it has traveled, but not exactly when and where.
This, Khan said, would also be more reassuring to the public.
The hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup company called True Mileage in California.
The company originally did not appear to help states in the taxation of drivers.
Rather, their goal was to gain a foothold in an emerging market for car insurance, where drivers are to pay based on the miles driven.
But the devices she tested are also interesting for road planners, because they do not work with GPS and only provide limited information, which is regularly uploaded via modem.
“People are more willing to participate if their speed and locations are not recorded,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Some of these public pilot programmes have made major mistakes.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to implement this.
In Oregon, planners are experimenting with giving drivers a number of choices.
You can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they choose no device at all and instead pay a flat fee based on the average miles driven by all the residents of the state.
Others hope to be able to sell the concept of a suspicious public by equipping the devices with more functions than with fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a device for taxation that can also be used to pay parking fees, have to pay insurance only for driven kilometers, and collect speed data from other vehicles in real time, thanks to which drivers can avoid traffic jams.
“Drivers would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits that the system offers,” the city’s planning document states.
However, some traffic planners wonder if all the talk about paying per mile is not just a huge distraction maneuver.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area, officials said Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by raising the fuel tax.
An additional one-time fee or an annual levy could be imposed on drivers with hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that consume little gasoline, so that they also pay a fair share.
“There is no reason for surgery if an aspirin is enough,” said Randy Rentschler, the Commission’s head of legislation and public affairs.
When we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers worry about their privacy and numerous other things.
