U.S. border: 'Super tunnel' to drug smuggling discovered
At the border between Mexico and the United States, investigators have discovered and shut down a “super tunnel” for drug smuggling.
According to U.S. customs authorities, the more than 500-metre-long tube between Tijuana and San Diego was equipped with electricity, rail tracks and a ventilation system.
Three suspects were arrested, eight tons of marijuana and nearly 150 kilograms of cocaine confiscated.
The tunnel was reportedly not yet in use.
"These cartels are stupid when they think they could dig under the radar," U.S. District Attorney General Laura Duffy said at a press conference outside a warehouse in San Diego where one end of the tunnel had been discovered.
Duffy said: "If you continue to build such tunnels and try to use them, we are determined to make that a huge waste of your dirty money."
Both the U.S. authorities and Mexican security forces are in a long-term fight against the drug cartels.
Since 2006, more than 77,000 people have been killed in Mexico in connection with drug crime.
Designed by experts
Due to the elaborate equipment of the tunnel, the investigators assume that it was designed by architects and engineers and that the construction took about a year.
The track system was equipped in such a way that electrically operated wagons could be used there.
On the Mexican side, the access is in a building that is 80 meters from the border.
According to authorities, a ladder leads 20 meters into the depth to the actual tunnel entrance.
The tunnel has a cross section of 1.20 meters high and 90 centimeters wide.
It would also have been suitable to promote illegal immigration towards the United States.
Two of the suspects were arrested in connection with the cocaine fund.
The third, a Mexican, was arrested for the confiscated marijuana.
All three are threatened with life imprisonment as a maximum penalty, officials said.
Eight such tunnels have been discovered since 2006, the San Diego press conference said.
This is the first time cocaine has been found in such a tunnel.
Usually, cocaine is smuggled in smaller amounts rather than through tunnels.
This shows the "despair" of drug gangs whose traditional routes have been cut, said Bill Sherman of the drug investigation DEA in San Diego.
They would do anything to get to the United States.
