Esa decides on large space missions: missions for billions
Remote planets, gravitational waves or black holes - European Space Agency experts must now agree on two major projects they want to start in the coming years.
There were 30 proposals to choose from, five are still in the race.
Distant worlds.
More than 1,000 planets in other stars have already been found by astronomers.
Whether there is life on at least some of them, no one knows.
The choice is difficult: Should we look for gravitational waves?
Or would you rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or searching for Earth-like planets and perhaps discovering extraterrestrial life?
These questions are being asked by the European Space Agency Esa.
For their "Cosmic Vision" program, they are looking for ideas for two major space projects that are designed to drive research forward decisively.
The budget for such "L-missions" is about one billion euros in each case.
The launch is expected to be in 2028 and 2034.
At the beginning of September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
Thirty ideas were debated, five of which have now come into closer election.
Numerous committees review the proposals, hook up with the researchers.
In the next few days, a final decision will be made by the scientific programme committee.
In total, Esa has selected four major questions to be answered by the missions of the Cosmic Vision programme initiated in 2007.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The exact processes in the formation of stars from large gas clouds – and thus also the formation of planets orbiting these stars – are still in the proverbial darkness.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can life arise there?
To address this issue, in 2017 the space telescope "Cheops" is to be launched, with which 500 already known planetary systems in our vicinity will be investigated in more detail.
But the possibilities are limited, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, astronomers could map Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres, thus searching for "biomarkers": gases that are considered an indication of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
In the end, this question should also provide information about the prerequisites for the emergence of life.
An important role is played by the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field, as well as the particle radiation emanating from it with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be examined exemplarily.
With the "Solar Orbiter", the Esa has already approved an M-Class mission (where the budget is about half a billion euros) for this question.
The probe is scheduled to launch in 2017 and closely observe the surface and activity of the Sun.
Of great interest to the researchers are also Jupiter and its moons.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the development of the solar system.
Esa is the first of three L missions in the Cosmic Vision program.
The spacecraft Juice (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) is expected to begin its voyage in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter and aims to investigate the planet’s atmosphere as well as the icy moons Europa, Kallisto and Ganymede.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
Space offers many ways to study matter under extreme conditions and to investigate whether the laws of nature known to us are still valid there.
Perhaps there are also deviations that could lead the physicists to a new theory under which all the known laws of nature can be united.
How was the universe created and what is it made of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was created by the Big Bang.
In addition to the matter common to us, consisting of stars, planets, and living beings like us, there is dark matter, whose gravity holds together galaxies and galaxy clusters, and dark energy, through whose action the expansion of the universe accelerates.
So far, researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first few seconds of the Big Bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy consist of.
With "Euclid", Esa has already approved an M-Mission, whose launch is scheduled for 2020.
Using a special telescope, the probe is designed to investigate the distribution of matter in the universe over the entire sky for the first time, allowing conclusions about the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could do the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection process.
The best chances of getting a permit as an L-mission, according to many experts, has "E-Lisa", a sophisticated concept for detecting gravitational waves.
This includes changes in the structure of space time that Albert Einstein predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to this day.
Elisa could do that, the scientists behind the project hope.
The mission includes a detector consisting of two or three probes, which is stationed in space.
Unlike systems on Earth, it could also detect gravitational waves that emerged during the Big Bang, thus providing new insights into the formation of the cosmos.
Four other proposals are still competing for the second L mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena", which is meant to explore black holes, "Icy Planets", another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism", a mission to measure the cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Finder", the Earth-like planet.
Proposals for sample transport back from Mars, for exploration of the moon, Venus and asteroids, and for solar physics have already been eliminated.
