What happens on the way with my email?
E-mail is an electronic letter.
Was e-mail technically implemented in the design of the Internet service similar to that of the traditional postal service?
When designing early Internet services, the focus was on making communication possible.
Therefore, the basic technical protocols did not provide a stable basis for a sound exchange of letters.
Therefore, a traditional email is more like an open postcard than a sealed letter.
If user "Anna" sends a mail to "Benni", are the two computers directly connected?
The e-mail program or browser of Anna sends the mail to the mail server of their service provider in the first step.
For example, if you have a Gmail account, that would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider that Benni uses.
On the route, the mail can run via several other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content to his provider.
Will traditional emails be read on their way through the web?
Most emails are read on the road by software robots several times.
The sender's provider usually checks whether the mail has a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also carried out on the recipient systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is an annoying and unwanted spam email that is immediately deleted or at least sorted away into a spam folder.
Do the robots have another task?
For systems like GMail, the robot also finds the information Google needs to place contextual advertising.
When Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google can display corresponding links to holiday offers.
Do unknown people read the emails?
The likelihood that unauthorized persons will read an email is extremely low.
But theoretically, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read electronic mail.
Law enforcement and intelligence agencies also have legal means of intercepting or noticing emails.
In addition, there are possible illegal espionage actions.
Is it possible to protect emails from read-only?
With an encryption according to the OpenPGP standard, an email can be effectively encrypted against read-on.
With great technical effort, it is also possible to conceal the metadata of an email communication, so that it is not even readily possible to recognize who has communicated with whom.
How important are Yahoo and Google in the e-mail market in Germany?
According to an August 2013 investigation by Convios Consulting, Yahoo and Google play only a minor role in the mailboxes that are mainly used privately.
