Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
It is controversial what is actually the beginning of puberty, but it is true that breast augmentation is accompanied by a growth boost before the age of eight.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates – something that a pediatrician can closely monitor.
If progressing faster, tests may be indicated by an endicronologist so that serious problems such as tumors or cysts can be ruled out.
There are treatment methods for delaying early menstruation and preventing another consequence: premature aging of bones, which can ultimately lead to growth inhibition and thus small body growth in adults.
Recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the rate of development, the rate of growth and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is restrained as far as medication is concerned, but he admits: “Suppressing puberty can alleviate behavioral problems and girls’ feelings of being different from their peers.”
The other big problem is understandable: parents just don’t want their very young daughters to have the period.
"They're worried about the risk of pregnancy or about how they handle the hygienic side," Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter had her days when she was ten.
Even though there were early signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was emotionally unprepared.
She came home frightened and excited from school because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many comprehensively published theories about the causes of early puberty.
But there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are responsible.
Boys get into puberty in the same way as girls.
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the obesity epidemic.
He supported the conduct of a 2001 study of girls aged six to nine, which establishes a link between body fat and adolescence.
Other studies support this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty more than their white peers.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to be influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another mystery: Although boys’ facial and puberty hair is growing earlier, the trend towards a full-fledged earlier puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference stressed the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common even in babies and toddlers.
“We need to be careful as we identify the true onset of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to ask their pediatrician for advice on how to talk to their child.
“This can mean that you have to have a conversation earlier than expected,” Kaplowitz advised.
