Pant houses boom in Singapore as the crisis has arrived in the middle class
In a pawn shop at the Bendemeer shopping mall in Singapore, Janani Amirthalinga exchanges a golden bracelet, a ring and a pair of earrings to pay her daughters’ school fees.
“My husband and I just bought a house, all my money is in it,” says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns 3,000 Singapore dollars (about 1,730 euros) each month as an administrative employee and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not sufficient, she explains.
In fact, demand in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is on the rise – is so high that ValueMax, where it traded, this week became the third pant house listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
Pledging jewelry is not only a quick way to get money – $1,300 Singapore in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, pledges in Singapore demand an effective annual interest rate of 17 percent, which is just over the 15.4 percent that United Overseas Bank demands, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawnshops offer the advantage that there is no need to check creditworthiness or proof of income, which is why loans are possible faster than banks.
That’s why millions of people in the region turn to pawnshops after families feel the pressure from rising costs of living and increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to loose financial policies in developed economies, low- and middle-income families are looking for pawnshops to make up for the difference in the booming economy.
This week, the rating agency Standard & Poor’s growing household debt, mainly due to rising mortgages, described as a risk factor for Asian banks’ creditworthiness.
Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest budget debt in Asia in relation to gross domestic product.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80 percent of GDP, an increase of 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also worried about the high consumer debt in Thailand, which just came out of a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed a continuing export weakness and a decline in consumer demand.
“Ultimately, this means that in the face of rising costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible,” says Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historic highs in gold prices over the past two years have heightened the trend of pledging personal items as people take the opportunity to turn family jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items in the city state’s 200 pawnshops are gold.
People say to themselves, "The gold price looks good, let's pledge Grandma's gold chain and get it back next month."
The largest Thai pawn shop operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20 percent customer growth in its stores in recent months.
The growth in the pledge business is so strong that ValueMax, the operator of the branch in Bendemeer and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only to neighboring Malaysia – where the company operates four houses – but also outside Asia, according to Yeah Lee Ching, Managing Director of ValueMax.
The company funded that with 60 percent of the $66 million it took this week with the IPO in Singapore.
While some lenders have fallen on the brink of high interest rates, Yeah explains that pawnshops not only offer cheaper interest rates than other lenders, but also do not directly increase debt.
"Customers borrow items they already own, and the liquefaction of personal valuables does not increase household training," she explains.
The pledge lending business is increasingly accepted in society as short-term, secured financing.
Also, not all people who use bonds are in financial difficulties.
Rich people from Singapore also come to ValueMax stores to pledge gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they get up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
We have clients from all walks of life.
“This includes wealthy people who borrow something for a business or investment in the short term, or small businesses who need to bridge cash flow bottlenecks,” says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
