FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices on airplanes (but do not make phone calls)
From departure to landing, air travelers can now use their electronic devices to read, work, play, listen to music and watch movies, but not make phone calls, according to the new guidelines issued Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the United States.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented depends on the respective airline, FAA staffer Michael Huerta told a press conference.
Airlines must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the flight crew training manuals as well as the regulations for storing the equipment in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the state of the plan, we could very soon approve the expanded use of electronic devices," the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers have to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They are not allowed to restart until the aircraft has reached a height of three kilometers and the captain gives the green light.
When entering the landing approach, passengers must turn it off again and must not take off again before the plane has landed.
Under the new directives, airlines whose aircraft are protected against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices even on take-off, landing and on the field, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft that have been upgraded to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the professional flight attendant association, welcomed the changes.
“If the new regulation is implemented safely – and we are working closely with the airline in this regard – both sides will benefit from it,” said Glading.
Honestly, we are tired of having to feel like a watchman on this issue.
Nevertheless, internet connections for surfing, exchanging emails, text messages or downloading data under three kilometers remained prohibited, the agency explained.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
So still no "Words With Friends", the Scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he had to publicly leave an American Airlines jet because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices such as laptops must continue to be stored, as there is a risk of injury if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phone calls during the flight are also prohibited.
The regulatory competence for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices at launch and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national traffic safety expert, told CBS News that mobile phones were still considered a risk.
“Mobile phones are really a problem, not just because they could potentially cause disruptions to navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that transmission from the air can also interfere with transmitter masts,” Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate this issue recommended last month that the government allow a wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure has increased on the FAA to loosen restrictions on use.
Critics such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill of Missouri argue that there are no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
In some studies, up to one-third of passengers forget or ignore the shutdown of the device.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air passengers in 1966, after reports of navigation and communication equipment failures by passenger-driven VHF radios became known, which at the time represented the latest technological trend.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA that they don’t care about electronic interference.
Airlines have been providing passengers with Wi-Fi for several years now when the flight height has been reached.
The aircraft adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also more insensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger planes should be suitable for greater use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit significantly less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, emit only minimal radiation when you flip.
However, when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
One of the advocates of easing restrictions on the use of devices by passengers is Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle e-readers and took a test flight to determine problems, but could not detect them.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using equipment.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believes the interference from the devices is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members said there were only isolated reports of pilots speaking for a failure of aircraft systems by the devices, and most of them are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order the disconnection of the devices by passengers when instrument landing under poor visibility conditions.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and described them as a reasonable fit for travelers who would be extensively equipped with technology today.
“We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience does not conflict with safety,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
