Scientists have been able to shed more light on the connection between a dog’s tail swing and his mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs with the tail swinged more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while it was the left side in nervous dogs.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “It is well known in humans that the left and right brains react differently to stimuli that provoke positive or negative emotions.”
Here we tried to look at this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just like in humans, the right half of the brain is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres play different roles in feelings.
To learn more about how dogs react to the lateral tail swing of their peers, the researchers monitored the animals while watching these films of other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged friends and analyzed the behavior.
Probably we'll soon understand why the tail moves in one direction, in the other
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed the dogs movies with dogs – either a true version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw how an otherwise expressionless dog moved the tail to the right (from the perspective of the wading dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail inclination was mainly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog that is fouling), then their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs would have learned from experience what movements they should be worried about and when not.
He said, “If you have different encounters with other dogs and the tail is more related to friendly behavior in one direction and the right side is more likely to produce a less friendly behavior, then you react based on these experiences.”
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers better understand their animal’s emotions.
John Bradshaw, an expert on dog behavior and guest scholarship at the University of Bristol’s Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, said this was not the first study to examine whether left and right were important to dogs.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right when it is a satisfied dog.
Another research paper at the University of Victoria in Canada said: “Dogs are more likely to go to a robot dog when their ‘tail’ swings left rather than right, rather than getting restless – exactly the opposite of the Italian study.”
According to his statement, the differences could be caused by the fact that the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could help, he explained.
"While there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two brain halves are used for different purposes, many of the details still need to be determined - and dogs are no exception," Bradshaw said.
Since their behavior is simply recorded, it will probably not take long before we understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
