I recognize the great and versatile things Obama has accomplished, from the passage of the Affordable Care Act for health insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, the end of the forced concealment of homosexuality in the army and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I too believe that the party-political blockade tactic has overturned too many aspirations to move our nation forward: immigration reform, a public health insurance option, and the closure of Guantanamo Bay, to name a few.
But after defending the Obama administration countless times against colleagues and acquaintances, I have reached the end of my attempts at explanation.
I have reached a point of political despair.
Republican blockade policy cannot explain why it is allowed to listen to foreign heads of state or kill innocent children by drones overseas.
It cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data on the privacy of Americans and why whistleblowers who disclose state misconduct are being punished.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, a U.S. citizen, was murdered without prosecution, nor why public funding and spending limits are being circumvented during the presidential elections.
It does not justify the results of a report that says the White House’s efforts to calm the media are the “most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.”
And recently, it can’t excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the passing of the Affordable Care Act.
I don't know if that's what I should have expected.
Whether I should have understood at 18 that government work could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it.
Obviously, the MP is not a predictable course, as an opposition party and random events such as the Newtown massacre shape the public debate.
But when I look at the above examples, they seem to be largely elected by the government itself.
And that bothers me the most.
I voted Obama again in 2012, not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney represented a confusing and uneducated alternative, he seemed unable to set his direction and positions.
I had the impression that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of future elections, would fulfill the hope we had heard of for so long.
