Tourism: Descent to the Romans
A sewage canal from the Roman era is preserved below Cologne at about 120 meters in length.
If you visit Cologne, you will not pass the cathedral.
The two towers rise to the sky about 157 meters, making it the second highest church building in Europe.
However, few visitors who admire the two filigree church towers know that there is a lot to discover under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in the underworld of Cologne.
The meeting point for his guided tours is the service center of Cologne-Tourismus directly at the cathedral.
The tour starts quite unspectacular: "We start in the underground car park," says Schulze.
In the 1970s the city fathers wanted a car-friendly city, and therefore only what was not too large remained of the remnants of the old city walls.
Most of the users of the car park nowadays also rush past the Roman remains and only park their car.
But if you take a closer look, you will find an archaeological site separated by metal lattices in the D2 park deck.
You can see about five meters high ruins of hand-plate-sized stones.
“They are remnants of the Roman city walls built in the second half of the first century AD,” Schulze says.
Before it goes back to daylight, Schulze lets the participants on the upper park level take a look into a dark shaft, 15 meters deep.
This is the fountain of the old dome, which unfortunately is hardly perceived.
The next stop of the tour is the praetorium, and here the participants go down again to the depths.
Here we are witnessing the seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the praetor of the CCAA.
What CCAA means, a visitor wants to know.
The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which in good German means "City of Roman law and City of Agrippinensians, founded under Emperor Claudius at the site of the altar for emperor worship".
And the praetorium is the former governor’s palace, the center of power of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the front room of the exhibition, a tunnel leads to the Roman wastewater canal, which is preserved here at a length of about 120 meters.
"You can quietly walk a bit along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want," Schulze encourages the guests.
There is still a surprise for Schulze.
After picking up the key at the checkout, he leads the group to a 16-meter-deep walkable shaft.
“We are now in the Mikwe, a ritual Jewish bath,” he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep in the ground to get to the groundwater, which was essential for the ritual washes.
To this day, in the lower end of the Mikwe, whose origins date back to the eighth century, different water levels can be seen by changing levels of the Rhine.
The Mikwe will be part of an archaeological zone on the Town Hall Square, for which construction work is to begin shortly.
However, there will be a few more years until it is completed.
