The disposable company does not think
The night was long, the music was loud and the mood was good, but at some point it was going home.
Only: In the stomachs of the people in the passenger and rear seat the hunger becomes noticeable.
Of course, one or the other cocktail or sparkling wine may be responsible for this!
What’s closer than chilled to the next drive-in to treat yourself to a little bit?
I admit, I’m happy to be there when it’s late at night or early in the morning.
A few fries, a cola, a burger - and then nothing like going home and going to bed!
On the way home, however, the obvious differences between me and other hungry disco-goers are noticeable.
Because what do you have to miss if you throw your fast food bags out of the car window with steady regularity?!
Especially on weekends, discarded paper bags are on roadsides and on parking lots.
“Why?” I wonder.
Are people too dumb to take the bags home or to the next trash can?
It’s not just that the paper is shaming the landscape.
Bags have also already obscured traffic facilities such as guideboards and caused accidents.
"Disposal society" does not think about this, but probably does not even know what this word actually means.
If you travel more often in the evening, especially with several people in the car, you know what a back seat can look like after busy nights: clothes, bottles and other garbage tower there.
There would be a few bags more or less even nothing - unlike the street, where no one wants to trample on the food remnants of others.
I see the day already coming when the cities and municipalities will be too stupid to clear their way - and the fast-food chains will have to demand a pledge for their bags.
Obama's retreat in health policy
After fierce criticism, President Obama made a retreat yesterday in his often repeated, unequivocal promise: “If you like your health insurance, then you can keep it.”
After hundreds of thousands received a letter of termination from their insurer, Republicans in recent days accused the president of deceiving the American public.
Yesterday, Obama relativized his original promise.
“The vast majority of citizens who have a working health insurance can keep it,” he said at a speech in Boston.
In response to the numerous media reports on the terminations, Obama urged those Americans who have received such communications to look around the free market for new insurance.
Most citizens could get better, more comprehensive health insurance at the same price or cheaper than predicted.
“They’re coming up with a better offer,” he said.
The government said it was not surprising that the five percent of the population who took out insurance themselves would have to look around for a different tariff because their contract did not meet the new standards under the Affordable Care Act.
“I want to tell these Americans very directly: they deserve better,” Sebelius said at a hearing before the House Energy and Trade Committee in Washington.
Sebelius, who is responsible for implementing the Affordable Care Act, said the launch of the online platform has been “miserable” since October.
“I’m just as frustrated and angry as everyone else,” she said.
I am determined to regain your trust.
