After more than three hours of hearing, Long Sebelius repeatedly asked why the Affordable Care Act's "architect" did not voluntarily give up a state-funded insurance policy to conclude a tariff at HealthCare.gov, which she now wants to sell to millions of Americans.
Government in Jerusalem not confirms attack on Syrian air base
A U.S. government official who wanted to remain anonymous told CNN on Thursday that Israeli fighter jets had attacked an air base in Syria’s Latakia the day before.
The target was "missiles and associated equipment" that the Israeli government feared were intended for Lebanon's Hezbollah, according to CNN.
Syrian and Lebanese media as well as the Arab broadcaster Al-Arabiya had previously reported that the base in the port city of Latakia had been fired on the night of Wednesday to Thursday, and blamed the Israelis for it.
The Israeli television channel Channel 2 showed satellite images of the base in Latakia, on which were seen Russian S-125 Newa missiles and a battery of SA-3 missiles, which according to Channel 2 have a range of 35 kilometers and can carry warheads up to 70 kilograms.
The government in Jerusalem has not officially confirmed the attack.
However, Reuters quotes an anonymous Israeli government official as saying he believes Israel carried out the attack, but is not sure.
A spokesman for the Israeli Ministry of Defense said: “We are not commenting on these reports.”
Journalist Ron Ben-Yishai stressed in the daily Yedioth Ahronoth that the Syrian regime had already tried to deliver ground-to-air missiles to Hezbollah earlier, in part successfully.
The Israeli government had repeatedly warned that any attempt by Syria to supply Hezbollah with chemical or other dangerous weapons would mean crossing a “red line” that a military response would follow.
John Kerry says in an unprecedented admission that US spying has “improperly gone too far”
With an unexpected admission, John Kerry suggested a softening of the U.S.’s defensive stance on its surveillance programs, saying the espionage had “inadequately gone too far” in certain cases.
The foreign minister also admitted that he and Barack Obama were responsible for switching to “autopilot” when the explosive revelations of whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA’s espionage activities became public.
Through the leaked information, the U.S. government has fallen into a diplomatic storm of outrage on the part of its allies.
In a video speech at the Open Government conference in London, Kerry said: “Of course, the President and I, and others in the government, have learned about some things that happened almost by autopilot, simply because of the ability to do so, which can be traced back to the Second World War and the difficult years of the Cold War and, of course, to 9/11.”
He was the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage had crossed a border, but also stressed that no rights had been abused.
He said, “In some cases, this has gone too far.”
The President is determined to create clarity and is therefore conducting a thorough investigation so that no one has to feel that abuse is taking place here.
I assure you that the rights of innocent persons will not be impaired in this process.
Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force of goodness and that many lives had been saved through its surveillance operations.
He added, “We are dealing with a new world where people are willing to blow themselves up.”
There is a radical extremism in the world that is focused on killing people, blowing up the air and attacking governments.
So what if you were able to intercept and stop it before it happened?
We have actually prevented plane crashes, attacks on buildings and the killing of people, because we have heard of such plans in advance.
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to dispel concerns about alleged American espionage and convince Europeans of the need to continue working with the U.S. on anti-terrorism efforts, as the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy of Connecticut said he spoke with representatives of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about their threats to stop participating in anti-terrorism organizations due to frustration over National Security Agency surveillance.
“It is very important for the national security interests of the United States that Europeans remain on board in view of our joint efforts to combat terrorism,” Murphy, who sits in the Senate as a Democrat for the first time and serves as chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on Foreign Relations and European Affairs, said in an interview in Washington.
I am also going to Europe to make it clear that we must continue to work together in the fight against terrorism, despite their anger about the NSA programs.
Media reports that the NSA has collected millions of phone data in Europe have strained relations with some U.S. allies, although the head of the intelligence service said this week that the reports were inaccurate and were based on a misunderstanding of the metadata collected by NATO allies and exchanged with the United States.
Other revelations cited documents released by Snowden that the NSA monitored the phone of Chancellor Angela Merkel and up to 34 other heads of state worldwide.
The head of the national intelligence services, James Clapper, defended espionage among allies as necessary, stating that this was common on both sides.
In all the turmoil, Murphy said his authority was preparing the congressional journey to take place this year, hoping the delegation would include members from both parties and chambers.
The names of the other participating MEPs are to be published in the coming days.
He said the exact itinerary was still being worked out.
While Murphy stressed that the purpose of the trip was to improve relationships, he also said that there would be some “serious words.”
He said European governments should be honest with their people about the kind of espionage programs they have been using themselves for years.
“While we can change our surveillance programs and thus better protect the rights of Europeans, they must also reconcile with the fact that we are not the only ones who are spying,” Murphy said.
Meanwhile, John Kerry is scheduled to travel to the Middle East and Poland over the weekend to deal with the resentment of the US strategy in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as the US surveillance activities.
